"255A":{"department":"EDUC","number":"255A","title":"Experimental Research Designs in Educational Research","description":"The course will cover the following topics: a) the logic of causal inference and the Fisher/Neyman/Rubin counterfactual causal model (Fisher, 1935; Heckman, 1979; Holland, 1986; Neyman, 1990; Rubin, 1978); b) randomized experiments; c) complex randomized experiments in education (cluster randomized trials, multi-site trials, staggered implementation via randomization, etc.); d) policy experiments with randomization; e) meta-analysis; and f) power in randomized experiments; g) the ethics and politics of randomized experiments.","min_units":3,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":210308,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Bettinger, E."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"8:30:00 AM","end":"10:20:00 AM","instructors":["Bettinger, E."],"location":""}],"id":16169}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"255B":{"department":"EDUC","number":"255B","title":"Causal Inference in Quantitative Educational and Social Science Research (SOC 257)","description":"Quantitative methods to make causal inferences in the absence of randomized experiment including the use of natural and quasi-experiments, instrumental variables, regression discontinuity, matching estimators, longitudinal methods, fixed effects estimators, and selection modeling. Assumptions implicit in these approaches, and appropriateness in research situations. Students develop research proposals relying on these methods. Prerequisites: exposure to quantitative research methods; multivariate regression.","min_units":3,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":204916,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Dee, T."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"2:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Dee, T."],"location":"160-317"}],"id":27746}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture","secondary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Bonilla, S."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"5:30:00 PM","end":"6:20:00 PM","instructors":["Bonilla, S."],"location":"160-317"}],"id":46857}],[]],"secondary_type":"Discussion"},
"255C":{"department":"EDUC","number":"255C","title":"Applied Quasi-Experimental Research in Education (SOC 258)","description":"Course will provide hands-on practice in analysis of data from experimental and quasi-experimental research designs, including a) instrumental variables estimators; b) regression discontinuity estimators; c) difference-in-difference estimators; d) matching estimators; e) fixed effects estimators; and f) panel data methods (including individual fixed effects models, lagged covariate adjustment models, growth models, etc.). Prerequisites: satisfactory completion of EDUC 255B, EDUC 257C or SOC 257.","min_units":3,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":210310,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Fahle, E."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Fahle, E.","reardon, s.","Doss, C."],"location":""}],"id":28461}]],"primary_type":"Lecture","secondary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Doss, C."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,true],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Fahle, E.","Doss, C."],"location":""}],"id":28473}]],"secondary_type":"Discussion"},
"256":{"department":"EDUC","number":"256","title":"Psychological and Educational Resilience Among Children and Youth (HUMBIO 149)","description":"Theoretical, methodological, and empirical issues pertaining to the psychological and educational resilience of children and adolescents. Overview of the resilience framework, including current terminology and conceptual and measurement issues. Adaptive systems that enable some children to achieve successful adaptation despite high levels of adversity exposure. How resilience can be studied across multiple levels of analysis, ranging from cell to society. Individual, family, school, and community risk and protective factors that influence children's development and adaptation. Intervention programs designed to foster resilient adaptation in disadvantaged children's populations.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":101747,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Padilla, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"12:20:00 PM","instructors":["Padilla, A."],"location":"School of Education 210"}],"id":28576}]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"257":{"department":"EDUC","number":"257","title":"Practicum in English-Spanish School & Community Interpreting (CHILATST 183X, EDUC 183)","description":"This practicum will assist students in developing a set of skills in English-Spanish interpreting that will prepare them to provide interpretation services in school and community settings. The course will build students' abilities to transfer intended meanings between two or more monolingual individuals of who are physically present in a school or community setting and who must communicate with each other for professional (and personal) purposes.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":214480,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Valdes, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"2:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Valdes, G."],"location":"School of Education 210"}],"id":28560}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Practicum"},
"260A":{"department":"EDUC","number":"260A","title":"Statistical Methods for Group Comparisons and Causal Inference (HRP 239, STATS 209)","description":"Critical examination of statistical methods in social science and life sciences applications, especially for cause and effect determinations. Topics: mediating and moderating variables, potential outcomes framework, encouragement designs, multilevel models, matching and propensity score methods, analysis of covariance, instrumental variables, compliance, path analysis and graphical models, group comparisons with longitudinal data. See http://rogosateaching.com/stat209/. Prerequisite: intermediate-level statistical methods.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":101759,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Rogosa, D."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,true],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"3:20:00 PM","instructors":["Rogosa, D.","Janson, L."],"location":"Sequoia Hall 200"}],"id":27676}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"260B":{"department":"EDUC","number":"260B","title":"Advanced Statistical Methods for Observational Studies (CHPR 290, STATS 266)","description":"Design principles and statistical methods for observational studies. Topics include: matching methods, sensitivity analysis, instrumental variables, graphical models, marginal structural models. 3 unit registration requires a small project and presentation. Computing is in R. Pre-requisites: HRP 261 and 262 or STAT 209 (HRP 239), or equivalent. See http://rogosateaching.com/somgen290/","min_units":2,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":216716,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Rogosa, D."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"2:30:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Rogosa, D."],"location":"Health Research & PolicyT138B"}],"id":47134}]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
